Grafana Dashboard Evidence
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of system metrics (CPU, memory, disk)
Familiarity with web browsers
Basic knowledge of monitoring concepts
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure Grafana on a Linux system
Set up Prometheus as a data source
Create operational dashboards with key metrics
Capture and document dashboard evidence
Understand visualization best practices
Environment Setup
You will use the Al Nafi bare-metal Linux cloud machine provided via the "Start Lab" button. All tools will be installed during this lab on a single machine.

Required Tools:

Grafana (latest stable version)
Prometheus (for metrics collection)
Node Exporter (for system metrics)
Task 1: Install and Configure Monitoring Stack
Step 1.1: Install Prometheus
# Download Prometheus
cd /tmp
wget https://github.com/prometheus/prometheus/releases/download/v2.47.0/prometheus-2.47.0.linux-amd64.tar.gz

# Extract and move to /opt
tar xvfz prometheus-2.47.0.linux-amd64.tar.gz
sudo mv prometheus-2.47.0.linux-amd64 /opt/prometheus
Step 1.2: Configure Prometheus
Create a basic configuration file:

sudo tee /opt/prometheus/prometheus.yml > /dev/null <<EOF
global:
  scrape_interval: 15s

scrape_configs:
  - job_name: 'prometheus'
    static_configs:
      - targets: ['localhost:9090']
  
  - job_name: 'node'
    static_configs:
      - targets: ['localhost:9100']
EOF
Step 1.3: Install Node Exporter
# Download Node Exporter
cd /tmp
wget https://github.com/prometheus/node_exporter/releases/download/v1.6.1/node_exporter-1.6.1.linux-amd64.tar.gz

# Extract and move
tar xvfz node_exporter-1.6.1.linux-amd64.tar.gz
sudo mv node_exporter-1.6.1.linux-amd64 /opt/node_exporter
Step 1.4: Create Systemd Services
Node Exporter Service:

sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/node_exporter.service > /dev/null <<EOF
[Unit]
Description=Node Exporter
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/opt/node_exporter/node_exporter
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF
Prometheus Service:

sudo tee /etc/systemd/system/prometheus.service > /dev/null <<EOF
[Unit]
Description=Prometheus
After=network.target

[Service]
Type=simple
ExecStart=/opt/prometheus/prometheus --config.file=/opt/prometheus/prometheus.yml --storage.tsdb.path=/opt/prometheus/data
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target
EOF
Step 1.5: Start Services
# Reload systemd and start services
sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl start node_exporter
sudo systemctl start prometheus
sudo systemctl enable node_exporter
sudo systemctl enable prometheus

# Verify services are running
sudo systemctl status node_exporter --no-pager
sudo systemctl status prometheus --no-pager
Step 1.6: Install Grafana
# Install dependencies
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y software-properties-common wget

# Add Grafana repository
wget -q -O - https://packages.grafana.com/gpg.key | sudo apt-key add -
echo "deb https://packages.grafana.com/oss/deb stable main" | sudo tee /etc/apt/sources.list.d/grafana.list

# Install Grafana
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y grafana

# Start Grafana
sudo systemctl start grafana-server
sudo systemctl enable grafana-server
Step 1.7: Verify Installation
# Check all services
echo "=== Service Status ==="
sudo systemctl is-active node_exporter
sudo systemctl is-active prometheus
sudo systemctl is-active grafana-server

# Check ports
echo "=== Port Status ==="
sudo netstat -tlnp | grep -E '9090|9100|3000'
Expected Output:

All services should show "active"
Ports 9090 (Prometheus), 9100 (Node Exporter), and 3000 (Grafana) should be listening
Task 2: Build Operational Dashboards
Step 2.1: Access Grafana
Open your web browser and navigate to:

http://localhost:3000
Default Credentials:

Username: admin
Password: admin
You will be prompted to change the password on first login.

Step 2.2: Add Prometheus Data Source
Click on the gear icon (Configuration) in the left sidebar
Select "Data Sources"
Click "Add data source"
Select "Prometheus"
Configure the following:
Name: Prometheus
URL: http://localhost:9090
Leave other settings as default
Click "Save & Test" - you should see "Data source is working"
Step 2.3: Create System Performance Dashboard
Click the "+" icon in the left sidebar
Select "Dashboard"
Click "Add new panel"
Panel 1: CPU Usage

Configure the panel:

Title: CPU Usage (%)
Query:
100 - (avg by (instance) (irate(node_cpu_seconds_total{mode="idle"}[5m])) * 100)
Visualization: Time series
Unit: Percent (0-100)
Legend: {{instance}}
Click "Apply" to save the panel.

Step 2.4: Add Memory Usage Panel
Click "Add panel" at the top
Select "Add new panel"
Panel 2: Memory Usage

Configure:

Title: Memory Usage
Query A (Used Memory):
node_memory_MemTotal_bytes - node_memory_MemAvailable_bytes
Query B (Total Memory):
node_memory_MemTotal_bytes
Visualization: Time series
Unit: Bytes (IEC)
Legend: Used Memory and Total Memory
Click "Apply".

Step 2.5: Add Disk Usage Panel
Click "Add panel"
Select "Add new panel"
Panel 3: Disk Usage

Configure:

Title: Disk Usage by Mount Point
Query:
100 - ((node_filesystem_avail_bytes{fstype!="tmpfs"} / node_filesystem_size_bytes{fstype!="tmpfs"}) * 100)
Visualization: Bar gauge
Unit: Percent (0-100)
Legend: {{mountpoint}}
Click "Apply".

Step 2.6: Add Network Traffic Panel
Click "Add panel"
Select "Add new panel"
Panel 4: Network Traffic

Configure:

Title: Network Traffic
Query A (Received):
rate(node_network_receive_bytes_total{device!="lo"}[5m])
Query B (Transmitted):
rate(node_network_transmit_bytes_total{device!="lo"}[5m])
Visualization: Time series
Unit: Bytes/sec (IEC)
Legend: RX - {{device}} and TX - {{device}}
Click "Apply".

Step 2.7: Organize Dashboard Layout
Arrange panels in a 2x2 grid by dragging them
Resize panels for better visibility
Click the disk icon (Save dashboard) at the top
Dashboard Name: System Performance Overview
Click "Save"
Step 2.8: Create Application Metrics Dashboard
Click the "+" icon and select "Dashboard"
Click "Add new panel"
Panel 5: Prometheus Targets Status

Configure:

Title: Monitoring Targets Status
Query:
up
Visualization: Stat
Value mappings:
0 = Down (Red)
1 = Up (Green)
Legend: {{job}}
Click "Apply".

Step 2.9: Add Query Rate Panel
Click "Add panel"
Panel 6: Prometheus Query Rate

Configure:

Title: Prometheus Query Rate
Query:
rate(prometheus_http_requests_total[5m])
Visualization: Time series
Unit: requests/sec
Legend: {{handler}}
Click "Apply" and save the dashboard as Monitoring Health.

Step 2.10: Configure Dashboard Settings
For each dashboard:

Click the gear icon (Dashboard settings) at the top
Set Time range: Last 15 minutes
Set Refresh interval: 30s
Click "Save dashboard"
Task 3: Capture Dashboard Evidence
Step 3.1: Prepare Screenshot Directory
# Create directory for screenshots
mkdir -p ~/grafana-evidence
cd ~/grafana-evidence
Step 3.2: Generate System Load
Open a new terminal and generate some activity:

# Generate CPU load
stress-ng --cpu 2 --timeout 60s &

# Generate disk I/O
dd if=/dev/zero of=/tmp/testfile bs=1M count=1024

# Monitor in real-time
watch -n 1 'uptime; free -h'
If stress-ng is not installed:

sudo apt-get install -y stress-ng
Step 3.3: Capture Dashboard Screenshots
Using Firefox (if available):

# Install Firefox if needed
sudo apt-get install -y firefox

# Take screenshot using Firefox
firefox --screenshot ~/grafana-evidence/system-performance.png http://localhost:3000/d/YOUR_DASHBOARD_UID
Alternative: Using command-line tool:

# Install screenshot tool
sudo apt-get install -y scrot

# Take full screen screenshot
sleep 5 && scrot ~/grafana-evidence/dashboard-fullscreen.png
Manual Screenshot Instructions:

Open Grafana dashboard in browser
Click the share icon (arrow) at the top of the dashboard
Select "Link" tab
Enable "Lock time range"
Copy the link
Use browser's screenshot feature (F12 > Ctrl+Shift+P > "Screenshot")
Save to ~/grafana-evidence/
